ator random variable__ $X_j$ <br><br>\n","\n","$X = X_1 + X_2 + \\cdots + X_n$ &emsp; &emsp; , \n","$X_j = \\begin{cases} 1 \\qquad \\text{, if $j$th trial success} \\\\ 0 \\qquad \\text{, otherwise} \\end{cases}$ <br>\n","&emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &ensp; , $X_j$'s are __i.i.d.__ $Bern(p)$ \n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","### Notion. &ensp; __Indicator__ <br><br>\n","\n","$\\; X_j \\;$ is called an ' indicator '. <br>\n",">It's just __indicating__ \" was the $j$'s trial success or failure ? \". <br>\n",">It's just a simple __encoding__ succees to $1$ and failure to $0$.\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","We can think of $\\; X \\;$ as $\\; X = X_1 + X_2 + \\cdots + X_n \\;$. what I wrote as the equation in indicator way is exactly same thing with as I wrote in words as \"the number of successes\" in story way. <br> \n","That's just how we count successes. I'm just plus $1$ each time there's a success and plus $0$ each time there's failure. <br><br>\n","\n","__It's very useful to think of distribution !__ though it could be subtle. <br>\n","__From a somewhat complicated distribution into very simple thing, a sum of $1$ and $0$,__ what we've done is broken down. So that's useful !\n","\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"1xSWz1BQeJvV","colab_type":"text"},"source":["### Notation. &ensp; __i.i.d.__ acronym <br><br>\n","\n","__i.i.d.__ means __\" independent and identically distributed \"__. <br><br>\n","\n","__' Independent '__ means all of each sub-event $X_j$ are independent each other <br>\n","In this case, we assume that the trials are independent and these are the indicatores of succsess for each trial, so those indicators should be independent. <br><br>\n","\n","__' Identically distributed '__ means all of these $X_j$'s have the same distribution. <br>\n","in this case, they're all $\\text {Bernoulli p}$. &ensp; ($1$ with probability $p$ and $0$ with probability $1-p$