determines all possible probabilities about $X$ !__ <br>\n","So if we wanted to know what's the probability that between 5 and 9 ... <br>\n","as long as we know the function CDF we could answer the question like that, <br>\n","all of those questions could be answered in terms of this CDP , $P(X \\leq x)$. <br>\n","what's the probability that $X$ does this, <br>\n","what's the probabitlity $X$ does that. <br><br>\n","\n","So __CDF__ is a way to __describe the distribution__ <br>\n","because it's __telling us the probabilities of different possible values for $X$__. <br>\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"Xsywk4cBRFgg","colab_type":"text"},"source":["### Notion. &ensp; Discrete R.V. and Continuous R.V. <br><br>\n","\n","#### What's the difference between a discrete R.V. and continuouse R.V. <br><br>\n","\n","  - Discrete &emsp; &emsp; : possible values you could list out. <br>\n","  &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &ensp; $a_1, a_2, a_3, \\cdots$  <br>\n","  <br>\n","  - Continuous &emsp; : possible values you could not list out <br>\n","  &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &emsp; &ensp; any $\\mathbb{R}$ , or any $\\mathbb{R}$ in some interval\n","\n","\n","<br>\n","\n",">__Complicated random variable ...?!__ <br>\n",">There are random variable that are neither discrete nor continuous. maybe you can kind of have a hybrid of discrete and continuous. But if we understand discrete R,V, and continuous R.V. then you can handle those hybrids as well. \n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"D6-cf-pmN4o2","colab_type":"text"},"source":["## 3$_{-2}$. PMF &ensp; (probability mass function) <br><br>\n","\n","\n","This is __only for discrete random variables.__ <br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","#### What's the PMF generally ? <br><br>\n","\n","\n","#### __Definition__ <br>\n","\n","$\\begin{align} && F(x) &= P(X = a_j) \\quad \\quad && \\text{for all j} \\\\ && &= p_j \\quad \\quad && p_j \\geq 0 \\quad and \\quad \\displaystyle \\sum_{j} p_j = 1 \\end{align}$ <br><br>\n","\n","\n","then, $F(x)$ is called __PMF__ of $x$. (probability mass function) <br>\n","We have to specify all of those probabilities for all $a_j$ ! (So there are pairs of $a_j$ and $p_j$) <br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","It is ... <br>\n","A blueprint for $X$. <br>\n","Saying just __\" what are the probabilities the $X$ take on certain values \"__ <br>\n","Describing that __the randomness of $X$__ <br>\n","written as $P(X=a_j) = p_j$ \n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","#### Notion ! <br>\n",">$X \\qquad \\qquad : \\;$ Random Variable <br>\n",">$P(X = a_j) \\; : \\;$ PMF <br><br>\n",">\n",">$x \\quad p \\quad ... \\;\\; : \\;$ instance ! (원소)\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","#### __Two conditions for PMF__ <br><br>\n","\n","  - $p_j \\geq 0$ <br>\n","  Because $p_j$ is a probability. <br><br>\n","\n","  - $\\displaystyle \\sum_{j} p_j = 1$ <br>\n","  We have listed out all the possible value through $a_j$, and we're assuming those $X's$ composed with $a_j$ is a complete list of the possibilies. <br>\n","  So sum of all the possibilities of all the possible $X's$ ($a_j$) has to be $1$.\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","If you want to go the other way around, you could say pick any numbers $p_j$ satisfying $p_j \\geq 0 \\quad and \\quad \\displaystyle \\sum_{j} p_j = 1$. And then that would define a valid PMF. <br>\n","So these two are the conditions for when is a PMF actually valid. \n","\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"-TrTDkO3Zah1","colab_type":"text"},"source":["### Notion. &ensp; PMF v.s. CDF <br><br>\n","\n","__PMF__ is only for discrete random variable case. <br>\n","__CDF__ is for any random variable case. <br><br>\n","\n","Usually it's much easier to use PMF than CDF. <br>\n","The reason is that __CDF__ is more __general__. <br><br>\n","\n","If you had a problem, find for the distribution. And what that means is either giving the CDF or giving the PMF if it's discret