Y \\sim Bin(m,p)$ &emsp; , and they two random variables are independent <br>\n","Then $X+Y \\sim Bin(n+m , \\; p)$ <br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","#### 1. Story proof &ensp; (structure?) <br><br>\n","\n","\n","#### 2. Mathematical proof : &ensp; Indicator R.V. <br><br>\n","\n","\n","$X = X_1 + X_2 + ... + X_n$ <br>\n","$Y = Y_1 + Y_2 + ... + Y_m$ <br><br>\n","\n","these all $X_j's$ and $Y_i's$ are all independent bernoulli $p$ random variables <br><br>\n","\n","then, <br>\n","$X+Y = \\displaystyle \\sum_{j=1}^n X_j + \\sum_{i=1}^m Y_i$ <br><br>\n","\n","What's the form this is in ?! <br>\n","This is just a sum of $n + m$ identically independent distributed bernoulli $p$'s. <br>\n","( just adding up in i.i.d. $Bern(p)$ with the same $p$ ! ) <br><br>\n","\n","According to the description of binomial distribution by indicator random variable, <br>\n","Taking a sum of $n$ i.i.d. $Bern(p)$ is a $Bin(n,p)$ ! <br><br>\n","\n","Here is $n+m$ of them, so we have $Bin(n+m, p)$ <br><br>\n","\n","$X+Y \\sim Bin(n+m,p)$ <br><br>\n","\n",">It's just adding up in i.i.d. $Bern(p)$ with the same $p$ and it's $Bin(n+m, p)$. Easy.<br>\n",">Because they're all independent ! It would get more complicated if they're not independent ! \n","\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"PfIGj47wQ_VC","colab_type":"text"},"source":["#### 3. Mathematical proof : &ensp; using PMF <br><br>\n","\n",">In third way, we have to actually do a calculation $\\quad$ ( useful calculation )\n","\n","<br>\n","\n","\n","I want to show thay $X+Y$ is binomial <br>\n","by computing its PMF. <br><br>\n","\n","So what I need to do is compute the probability that $P(X+Y=k)$, <br>\n","and if this is of the same binomial form, then that equation would be true. <br>\n","If not it has contradiction. (something's wrong) <br><br>\n","\n","\n","[ 25:30 ~ ] <br>\n","\n","<br>\n","\n","$X+Y$ , <br>\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ Add two R.V. ? $\\quad$ No... <br>\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ In Statistics, <br>\n","$\\qquad$ It's a Convolution (not same as 'convoluted'). We'll learn it later. <br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","Same strategy <br>\n","Wishful thinking $\\quad$ ( 가정! conditioning! ) <br><br>\n","\n","\n","What do we wish that we knew ? <br><br>\n","\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ Wanna have knew observed one of X or Y <br>\n","$\\qquad$ ( To make this Add problem be simple ) <br><br>\n","\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ then, by Law of Total probability <br>\n","$\\qquad$ this can be described simple about $Y$ with conditioning on $X$ <br><br>\n","\n","$\\begin{align} P(X+Y=k) \\quad &= \\displaystyle \\sum_{j=0}^k P(X+Y=k \\; | \\; X=j) \\; P(X=j) \\qquad &&\\text{... by LOTP} \\\\ \n","&= \\sum_{j=0}^k P(Y=k-j) \\; | \\; X=j) \\; \\binom{n}{j}p^jq^{n-j} &&\\text{... by $P(X=j)$ is PMF of Binomial}\\\\\n","&= \\sum_{j=0}^k P(Y=k-j) \\; \\binom{n}{j}p^jq^{n-j} &&\\text{... by independence} \\\\\n","&= \\sum_{j=0}^k \\binom{m}{k-j} p^{k-j}q^{m-k+j} \\binom{n}{j}p^jq^{n-j} &&\\text{... by $P(Y=k-j)$ is PMF of Binomial} \\\\ \n","&= p^k q^{m+n-k} \\sum_{j=0}^k \\binom{m}{k-j} \\binom{n}{j} &&\\text{... just simplifying} \\\\\n","&= p^k q^{m+n-k} \\binom{m+n}{k} &&\\text{.. by Vandermonde !} \\\\ \\\\\n","&\\Rightarrow \\text{that's exactly PMF of the binomial m+n !} \\end{align}$ <br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","So that's true ! <br>\n","> 이게 이항정리 ?!\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n",">$P(X=j)$ is PMF of Bernoulli dist. of X ! <br>\n","\n",">Key fact : $X$ and $Y$ are independent ! <br>\n",">( We haven't known the formal definition of independence for R.V. yer ..! ) <br>\n",">But, just by the definition of Independence <br>\n",">\" $X$ and $Y$ are Independent \" means that $X$ gives no information whatsoever about $Y$ <br>\n",">So conditioning on $X=j$ has no effect to $Y$. it tells nothing about $Y$ <br>\n",">$\\rightarrow \\quad$ we can ignore this condition !\n","\n",">$\\displaystyle \\sum_{j=0}^k \\binom{m}{k-j} \\binom{n}{j} \\quad = \\binom{m+n}{k}$ 