ions, (like PMF) <br>\n",">Just understanding the story !\n","\n",">We see about Hypergeometric dist. more later <br>\n",">( there're three versions of Hyper Geometric distribution story ? )\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","__PMF__ <br><br>\n","\n","$\\quad P(X=k) = \\frac{\\binom{w}{k} \\binom{b}{n-k}}{\\binom{w+b}{n}} \\qquad , 0 \\leq k \\leq w \\quad , 0 \\leq n-k \\leq b$\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","__STORY__ <br><br>\n","\n","Picking one following $Bern(p)$ dist., <br>\n","whose sampling without replacement <br><br>\n","\n","\" without replacement \" \n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ The initial environment changes <br>\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ It is ' not independent ' <br><br>\n","\n","\n",">__Binomial distribution__ <br><br>\n",">\n",">Picking one following $Bern(p)$ dist., <br>\n",">whose sampling with replacement <br>\n",">(pick one and put it back) <br><br>\n",">\n",">If you pick one and put it back, <br>\n",">the initial environment becomes reset. <br>\n",">It is ' independent '\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"t70V_gdTThVC","colab_type":"text"},"source":["### Key distinction between Hypergeometric and Binomial <br><br>\n","\n","\n","The key is \" REPLACEMENT \" <br>\n","( trials are \" INDEPENDENT \" , as a result of replacement ) <br><br>\n","\n","  - Binomial <br><br>\n","\n","  Sampling with replacement $\\quad$ ( reset sample-space ) <br>\n","  and trials are idenpendent <br>\n","  >when picking a marble and puting it back each time repeatedly, <br>\n","  >you want the distribution for the number of white marble. <br>\n","  >Then the trials are independent\n","\n","  <br>\n","\n","  - Hypergeometric <br><br>\n","\n","  Sampling without replacement $\\quad$ ( no reset ) <br>\n","  and trials are not independent <br>\n","  >when picking marble and not putting it back each time repeatedly, <br>\n","  >you want the distribution for the number of white marble. <br>\n","  >Then the trials are not independent.\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","### Connection between Hypergeometric and Binomial <br><br>\n","\n","\n","If sample-space is big enough (like 1 billion), <br>\n","( so our sample is very small (like 10) compared to the smaple-space ) <br><br>\n","\n","then, when we're pickng 2 samples out of the sample-sapce, <br>\n","it's extremely unlikely that we would pick the same marble more than once ! \n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","$\\text{Hypergeomatric} \\quad \\rightarrow \\quad \\text{Binomial} \\qquad \\text{, if sample-space $n$ is large enough}$ <br><br>\n","\n","So it must be that sampling with replacement and without replacement should behave very similarly there. <br>\n","Mathematically the Hypergeometric should be approximately Binomial ! <br>\n","( There are no much difference between them ) <br>\n","\n",">We can derivate it mathmatically, but here we could understand intuitively.\n","\n","\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"colab_type":"text","id":"iboP6OiZT2g2"},"source":["### __Validation checking__ of the Hypergeometric dist. $\\quad : \\;$ \" Is this valid PMD ? \" <br><br>\n","\n","  1. Is this non-negative ? <br>\n","  This is non-negative <br><br>\n","\n","\n","  2. does The sum of all ~ equal to $1$ ? <br>\n","  The sum of this over all possible $k$ is to 1 <br><br>\n","\n","  $\\begin{align} \\displaystyle \\sum_{k=0}^w P(X=k) \\quad &= \\sum_{k=0}^w \\frac{\\binom{w}{k} \\binom{b}{n-k}}{\\binom{w+b}{n}} \\\\\n","  &= \\frac{1}{\\binom{w+b}{n}} \\sum_{k=0}^w \\binom{w}{k} \\binom{b}{n-k}\\qquad &&... \\quad \\binom{w+b}{n} \\text{ is a constent} \\\\\n","  &= 1 \\qquad &&... \\quad \\sum_{k=0}^w \\binom{w}{k} \\binom{b}{n-k} = \\binom{w+b}{n} \\text{ by Vandermonde !} \\end{align}$\n","\n","\n","\n","<br><br><br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"colab_type":"text","id":"yaapcWkScnxU"},"source":["## 3. CDF of distribution &ensp; (Cumulative ) <br><br>\n","\n","It is ... <br>\n","Saying just &ensp; __\" what's the probability that $X$ takes in some range of value \"__ <br>\n","Written as &emsp; $P(X \\leq k)$ \n","\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","  - Continuous case <br>\n","  <img src=\"https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1go1u4aKDaGhgtyOFNcP_VxspFYn4heMV\" alt=\"8-01\" width=\"200\"> <br>\n","    - converging to $-\\infty$ or $\\infty$ <br>\n","    - continous value curve <br><br>\n","\n","  - Discrete case <br>\n","  <img src=\"https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1sDYOx9HpDzEnQbeRZyyHhYPTLQ3IXIj-\" alt=\"8-02\" width=\"200\"> <br>\n","    - No need to converge <br>\n","    - discrete value lines\n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"We7CD0JKTd8O","colab_type":"text"},"source":["### CDF <br><br>\n","\n","\n","CDF : $F(x) = P(X \\leq x) \\quad$ , as a function of real $x$\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","#### Discrete case of CDF <br><br>\n","\n","\n","<img src=\"https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1sx5-AknwVmMIGwb3aXJRg-PQkeD_Oqpz\" alt=\"9-01\" width=\"300\"> \n","\n","<br>\n","\n","x-axis : possible values\n","  - any non-negative real values (infinite) <br>\n","  - it can't be nevative (negative side in a graph is 0) <br><br>\n","\n","y-axis : probabilities <br>\n","  - values are discrete <br>\n","  - limit to 1 \n","\n","<br><br><br>\n","\n","\n","\n","#### Cennection of PMF and CDF <br><br>\n","\n","\n","We can see the relation of them geometrically in the graph. <br><br>\n","\n","From the CDP, we could recover the PMF. <br>\n","From the PMF, we could recover the CDP. $\\quad$ (just by summing things up) <br>\n",">We'll talk about little more about that.\n","\n","<br>\n","\n","$\\qquad$ \" CDF give you the entire distribution ! \" <br>\n","$\\rightarrow \\quad$ That means from the CDF you can compute any probability you want\n","\n","<br><br>\n","\n","\n","#### Example : find PMF using CDF <br><br>\n","\n","\n","Find $P(1 \\leq X \\leq 3)$ using $F$ <br><br>\n","\n","$P(X \\leq 1) + P(1 < X